{"_id": "32693324|None", "id": "32693324", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Environ. Pollut.; 2020 Jul 15 ; 266 (Pt 2) 115250. doi:10.1016/j.envpol.2020.115250", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Saha J, Chouhan P, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Indoor air pollution (IAP) and pre-existing morbidities among under-5 children in India: are risk factors of coronavirus disease (COVID-19)?", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "children", "locations": [{"offset": 70, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 109, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 130, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 141, "text": "Globally, the Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak is linked with air pollution of both indoor and outdoor environments and co-morbidities conditions of human beings. To find out the risk factor zones associated with Coronavirus disease among under-five children using pre-existing morbidity conditions and indoor air pollution (IAP) environmental factors and also with current fatality and recovery rate of COVID-19 disease in India. Data was utilized from the 4th round of the National Family Health Survey (NFHS), 2015-16, and from the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare (MoHFW) on 18th May 2020. Mean, standard deviation, and Z-score statistical methods have been employed to find out the risk factor zones i.e. to execute the objective. Findings of this study are, the states and UTs which have more likely to very higher to higher risk factors or zones of Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) are Mizoram (1.4), Meghalaya (1.27), Uttarakhand (0.92), West Bengal (0.73), Uttar Pradesh (0.66), Jammu and Kashmir (0.44), Odisha (0.33), Madhya Pradesh (0.21), Jharkhand (0.20), Bihar (0.19), Maharashtra (0.16 risk score), compared to UTs like Assam (-0.12), Rajasthan (-0.13), Goa (-0.14), Manipur (-0.17), Chandigarh (-0.19), Haryana (-0.22), Delhi (-0.27) have moderate risk factors of COVID-19, and the states and UTs like Daman and Diu (-1.18), Sikkim (-0.98), Andaman and Nicobar Islands (-0.84), Kerala (-0.69), Dadra and Nagar Haveli (-0.68), Arunachal Pradesh ( 0.-53), Karnataka (-0.42), and Nagaland (-0.36) have very low-risk zones of COVID-19 deaths. From a research viewpoint, there is a prerequisite need for epidemiological studies to investigate the connection between indoor air pollution and pre-existing morbidity which are associated with COVID-19. Well-built public health measures, including rapidly searching in high focus areas and testing of COVID-19, should be performed in vulnerable areas of COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 155, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 176, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 297, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 361, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "children", "locations": [{"offset": 398, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 552, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 1009, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1030, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1432, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1690, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "deaths", "locations": [{"offset": 1699, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1903, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 2011, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 2064, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693324, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D018352", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@9606", "disease@MESH:D003643"], "journal": "Environ. Pollut.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Saha J", "Chouhan P"]}
{"_id": "32693298|None", "id": "32693298", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Eur J Med Chem; 2020 Jul 15 ; 203 112647. doi:10.1016/j.ejmech.2020.112647", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Kouznetsov VV, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "COVID-19 treatment: Much research and testing, but far, few magic bullets against SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 82, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 93, "length": 11}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 106, "text": "The new virus of the of beta-Coronaviruses genus, SARS-CoV-2, is the causative agent of coronavirus disease-2019 (COVID-19) and is winning a proverbial chess match against all players simultaneous, including physicians, clinicians, pathologists, doctors, scientists, economists, athletes and politicians. The COVID-19 outbreak has seriously threatened public health, killing the most vulnerable persons and causing general panic. To stop this disease, effective remedies (i.e., drugs, vaccines, personal protection elements, etc.) are urgently required. Unfortunately, no registered specific therapies (including antiviral therapies, immune-modulating agents and vaccines) are currently available to treat coronavirus infections, highlighting an urgent need for therapeutics targeting SARS-CoV-2. In this work, fourteen existing small molecule drugs or/and experimental drugs selected by experts and examined from the point of view of bioavailability via the Lipinski-Veber rules and assessment of their physicochemical descriptors. The aim of this study is to discover selected pattern similarities and peculiar characteristics that could be useful for antiviral drug optimization, drug combination or new antiviral agent design.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "694002", "type": "Species"}, "text": "beta-Coronaviruses", "locations": [{"offset": 130, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 156, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease-2019", "locations": [{"offset": 194, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 220, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "4502", "type": "Species"}, "text": "chess", "locations": [{"offset": 258, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 415, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "persons", "locations": [{"offset": 501, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus infections", "locations": [{"offset": 812, "length": 22}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 891, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693298, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D018352", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@9606", "species@4502", "species@2697049", "species@11118", "species@694002"], "journal": "Eur J Med Chem", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Kouznetsov VV"]}
{"_id": "32693294|None", "id": "32693294", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Eur J Med Chem; 2020 Jul 15 ; 203 112653. doi:10.1016/j.ejmech.2020.112653", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Nebigil CG, Moog C, Vagner S, Benkirane-Jessel N, Smith DR, D\u00e9saubry L, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Flavaglines as natural products targeting eIF4A and prohibitins: From traditional Chinese medicine to antiviral activity against coronaviruses.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "Flavaglines", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronaviruses", "locations": [{"offset": 129, "length": 13}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 144, "text": "Flavaglines are cyclopenta[b]benzofurans found in plants of the genus Aglaia, several species of which are used in traditional Chinese medicine. These compounds target the initiation factor of translation eIF4A and the scaffold proteins prohibitins-1 and 2 (PHB1/2) to exert various pharmacological activities, including antiviral effects against several types of viruses, including coronaviruses. This review is focused on the antiviral effects of flavaglines and their therapeutic potential against severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2).", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "Flavaglines", "locations": [{"offset": 144, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "cyclopenta[b]benzofurans", "locations": [{"offset": 160, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronaviruses", "locations": [{"offset": 527, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "flavaglines", "locations": [{"offset": 593, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2", "locations": [{"offset": 645, "length": 47}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 694, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693294, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@11118", "species@2697049", "chemical@-"], "journal": "Eur J Med Chem", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Nebigil CG", "Moog C", "Vagner S", "Benkirane-Jessel N", "Smith DR", "D\u00e9saubry L"]}
{"_id": "32693284|None", "id": "32693284", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Sci. Total Environ.; 2020 Jul 14 ; 744 140911. doi:10.1016/j.scitotenv.2020.140911", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Rimoldi SG, Stefani F, Gigantiello A, Polesello S, Comandatore F, Mileto D, Maresca M, Longobardi C, Mancon A, Romeri F, Pagani C, Cappelli F, Roscioli C, Moja L, Gismondo MR, Salerno F, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Presence and infectivity of SARS-CoV-2 virus in wastewaters and rivers.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 28, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 72, "text": "The presence of SARS-CoV-2 in raw wastewaters has been demonstrated in many countries affected by this pandemic. Nevertheless, virus presence and infectivity in treated wastewaters, but also in the receiving water bodies are still poorly investigated. In this study, raw and treated samples from three wastewater treatment plants, and three river samples within the Milano Metropolitan Area, Italy, were surveyed for SARS-CoV-2 RNA detection by means of real time RT-PCR and infectivity test on culture cells. SARS-CoV-2 RNA was detected in raw, but not in treated wastewaters (four and two samples, respectively, sampled in two dates). The isolated virus genome was sequenced, and belonged to the strain most spread in Europe and similar to another found in the same region. RNA presence in raw wastewater samples decreased after eight days, probably following the epidemiological trend estimated for the area. Virus infectivity was always null, indicating the natural decay of viral pathogenicity in time from emission. Samples from receiving rivers (three sites, sampled in the same dates as wastewaters) showed in some cases a positivity to real time RT-PCR, probably due to non-treated, or inefficiently treated discharges, or to the combined sewage overflows. Nevertheless, also for rivers infectivity was null. Risks for public health should be limited, although a precautionary approach to risk assessment is here advocated, giving the preliminary nature of the presented data.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "6", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 88, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D014867", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "water", "locations": [{"offset": 280, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "8", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 489, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "9", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 582, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693284, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["chemical@MESH:D014867", "species@2697049"], "journal": "Sci. Total Environ.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Rimoldi SG", "Stefani F", "Gigantiello A", "Polesello S", "Comandatore F", "Mileto D", "Maresca M", "Longobardi C", "Mancon A", "Romeri F", "Pagani C", "Cappelli F", "Roscioli C", "Moja L", "Gismondo MR", "Salerno F"]}
{"_id": "32693269|None", "id": "32693269", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Sci. Total Environ.; 2020 Jul 17 ; 744 141012. doi:10.1016/j.scitotenv.2020.141012", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Son JY, Fong KC, Heo S, Kim H, Lim CC, Bell ML, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Reductions in mortality resulting from reduced air pollution levels due to COVID-19 mitigation measures.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 14, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 75, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 105, "text": "To control the novel coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak, state and local governments in the United States have implemented several mitigation efforts that resulted in lower emissions of traffic-related air pollutants. This study examined the impacts of COVID-19 mitigation measures on air pollution levels and the subsequent reductions in mortality for urban areas in 10 US states and the District of Columbia. We calculated changes in levels of particulate matter with aerodynamic diameter no larger than 2.5 mum (PM2.5) during mitigation period versus the baseline period (pre-mitigation measure) using the difference-in-difference approach and the estimated avoided total and cause-specific mortality attributable to these changes in PM2.5 by state and district. We found that PM2.5 concentration during the mitigation period decreased for most states (except for 3 states) and the capital. Decreases of average PM2.5 concentration ranged from 0.25 mug/m3 (4.3%) in Maryland to 4.20 mug/m3 (45.1%) in California. On average, PM2.5 levels across 7 states and the capital reduced by 12.8%. We estimated that PM2.5 reduction during the mitigation period lowered air pollution-related total and cause-specific deaths. An estimated 483 (95% CI: 307, 665) PM2.5-related deaths was avoided in the urban areas of California. Our findings have implications for the effects of mitigation efforts and provide insight into the mortality reductions can be achieved from reduced air pollution levels.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "novel coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 120, "length": 25}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 147, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 363, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 449, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 804, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "PM2.5", "locations": [{"offset": 890, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "deaths", "locations": [{"offset": 1319, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "deaths", "locations": [{"offset": 1377, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 1528, "length": 9}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693269, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643", "chemical@-"], "journal": "Sci. Total Environ.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Son JY", "Fong KC", "Heo S", "Kim H", "Lim CC", "Bell ML"]}
{"_id": "32693249|None", "id": "32693249", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Public Health; 2020 Jul 07 ; 185 261-263. doi:10.1016/j.puhe.2020.06.056", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Bray I, Gibson A, White J, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Coronavirus disease 2019 mortality: a multivariate ecological analysis in relation to ethnicity, population density, obesity, deprivation and pollution.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Coronavirus disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 25, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D009765", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "obesity", "locations": [{"offset": 117, "length": 7}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 153, "text": "BACKGROUND: There is emerging evidence about characteristics that may increase the risk of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) mortality, but they are highly correlated. METHODS: An ecological analysis was used to estimate associations between these variables and age-standardised COVID-19 mortality rates at the local authority level. RESULTS: Ethnicity, population density and overweight/obesity were all found to have strong independent associations with COVID-19 mortality, at the local authority level. DISCUSSION: This analysis provides some preliminary evidence about which variables are independently associated with COVID-19 mortality and suggests that others (deprivation and pollution) are not directly linked. It highlights the importance of multivariate analyses to understand the factors that increase vulnerability to COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease 2019", "