{"_id": "32693111|None", "id": "32693111", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J Dent; 2020 Jul 18 103434. doi:10.1016/j.jdent.2020.103434", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Ren Y, Feng C, Rasubala L, Malmstrom H, Eliav E, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Risk for dental healthcare professionals during the COVID-19 global pandemic: an evidence-based assessment.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 52, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 108, "text": "OBJECTIVES: Heightened anxiety among dental healthcare professionals (DHPs) during the COVID-19 pandemic stems from uncertainties about the effectiveness of personal protective equipment (PPE) against dental aerosols and risk levels of asymptomatic patients. Our objective was to assess the risks for DHPs providing dental care during the pandemic based on available scientific evidence. METHODS: We reviewed the best available evidence and estimated the annualized risk (p=das(1-1-p0p1(1-e)yn) for a DHP during the COVID-19 pandemic based on the following basic parameters: p0, the prevalence of asymptomatic patients in the local population; p1, the probability that a DHP gets infected by an asymptomatic patient; e, the effectiveness of the PPE; s, the probability of becoming symptomatic after getting infected from asymptomatic patient; da, the probability of dying from the disease in age group a; n, number of patients seen per day; and y, number of days worked per year. RESULTS: With the assumption that DHPs work fulltime and wear a N95 mask, the annualized probability for a DHP to acquire COVID-19 infection in a dental office, become symptomatic, and die from the infection is estimated at 1:13,000 (0.008%). CONCLUSIONS: Risk of COVID-19 transmission in dental office is very low based on available evidence on effectiveness of PPE and prevalence of asymptomatic patients. Face shields and pre-procedure oral rinses may further reduce the risks. CLINICAL SIGNIFICANCE: DHPs should follow guidelines on pre-appointment protocols and on PPE use during dental treatments to keep the risk low.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D001007", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "anxiety", "locations": [{"offset": 131, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 195, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 357, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "DHPs", "locations": [{"offset": 409, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "1807", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "20359"}, "text": "DHP", "locations": [{"offset": 609, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 718, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "1807", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "20359"}, "text": "DHP", "locations": [{"offset": 779, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patient", "locations": [{"offset": 816, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patient", "locations": [{"offset": 942, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1026, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "DHPs", "locations": [{"offset": 1122, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "1807", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "20359"}, "text": "DHP", "locations": [{"offset": 1195, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1486, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "DHPs", "locations": [{"offset": 1592, "length": 4}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693111, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:D001007", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "chemical@-", "gene@1807"], "journal": "J Dent", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Ren Y", "Feng C", "Rasubala L", "Malmstrom H", "Eliav E"]}
{"_id": "32693089|None", "id": "32693089", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Int. J. Infect. Dis.; 2020 Jul 18 . doi:10.1016/j.ijid.2020.07.016", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "de Sousa E, Ligeiro D, L\u00e9rias JR, Zhang C, Agrati C, Osman M, El-Kafrawy SA, Azhar EI, Ippolito G, Wang FS, Zumla A, Maeurer M, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Mortality in COVID-19 disease patients: Correlating Association of Major histocompatibility complex (MHC) with severe acute respiratory syndrome 2 (SARS-CoV-2) variants.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 13, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "6", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 30, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 148, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 170, "text": "As the 2019 (COVID-19) pandemic caused by the novel coronavirus, SARS-CoV-2 spreads globally, differences in adverse clinical management outcomes have been associated with associated with age >65years, male gender, and co-morbidities such as smoking, diabetes, hypertension, cardiovascular comorbidity and immunosuppression. Ethnicity has been the focus of attention after data from the United Kingdom showed a disproportionate number of deaths among healthcare workers from black, Asian and other ethnic minority backgrounds (1). In addition to ethnicity, socio-economic factors, prior vaccinations and exposure to other coronaviruses, other factors need to be considered to explain geographical and regional variations in susceptibility, severity of clinical expression of COVID-19 disease and outcomes. In the United States there have been disproportionate COVID-19 death rates among African Americans at around 2.6 times higher than that of other groups. Although these data could be due to multiple cultural and socioeconomic factors an underlying genetic susceptibility to SARS-CoV-2 infection may be a factor.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 183, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "novel coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 216, "length": 17}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 235, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 421, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D006973", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "hypertension", "locations": [{"offset": 431, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "deaths", "locations": [{"offset": 608, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronaviruses", "locations": [{"offset": 792, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 945, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1030, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "death", "locations": [{"offset": 1039, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2 infection", "locations": [{"offset": 1249, "length": 20}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693089, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D006973", "species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643", "disease@MESH:D003920", "species@2697049", "species@11118"], "journal": "Int. J. Infect. Dis.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["de Sousa E", "Ligeiro D", "L\u00e9rias JR", "Zhang C", "Agrati C", "Osman M", "El-Kafrawy SA", "Azhar EI", "Ippolito G", "Wang FS", "Zumla A", "Maeurer M"]}
{"_id": "32693079|None", "id": "32693079", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Curr. Biol.; 2020 Jul 20 ; 30 (14) 822-. doi:10.1016/j.cub.2020.06.037", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Kantermann T, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Behavior: How a Global Social Lockdown Unlocks Time for Sleep.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 63, "text": "Two new studies show that the social lockdown imposed as a result of the SARS-CoV-2 pandemic has helped unlock more time for sleep. Although daily stress during the lockdown increased, and sleep quality decreased, sleep behaviour was generally healthier.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 136, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693079, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@2697049"], "journal": "Curr. Biol.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Kantermann T"]}
{"_id": "32693068|None", "id": "32693068", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Curr. Biol.; 2020 Jul 20 ; 30 (14) 797-. doi:10.1016/j.cub.2020.06.022", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Wright KP, Linton SK, Withrow D, Casiraghi L, Lanza SM, Iglesia H, Vetter C, Depner CM, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Sleep in university students prior to and during COVID-19 Stay-at-Home orders.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 49, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 79, "text": "Sleep health has multiple dimensions including duration, regularity, timing, and quality [1-4]. The Coronavirus 2019 (COVID-19) outbreak led to Stay-at-Home orders and Social Distancing Requirements in countries throughout the world to limit the spread of COVID-19. We investigated sleep behaviors prior to and during Stay-at-Home orders in 139 university students (aged 22.2 +- 1.7 years old [+-SD]) while respectively taking the same classes in-person and remotely. During Stay-at-Home, nightly time in bed devoted to sleep (TIB, a proxy for sleep duration with regard to public health recommendations [5]) increased by ~30 min during weekdays and by ~24 mins on weekends and regularity of sleep timing improved by ~12 min. Sleep timing became later by ~50 min during weekdays and ~25 min on weekends, and thus the difference between weekend and weekday sleep timing decreased - hence reducing the amount of social jetlag [6,7]. Further, we find individual differences in the change of TIB devoted to sleep such that students with shorter TIB at baseline before the first COVID-19 cases emerged locally had larger increases in weekday and weekend TIB during Stay-at-Home. The percentage of participants that reported 7 h or more sleep per night, the minimum recommended sleep duration for adults to maintain health [5] - including immune health - increased from 84% to 92% for weekdays during Stay-at-Home versus baseline. Understanding the factors underlying such changes in sleep health behaviors could help inform public health recommendations with the goal of improving sleep health during and following the Stay-at-Home orders of the COVID-19 pandemic.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "8", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Coronavirus 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 179, "length": 16}]}, {"id": "9", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 197, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 335, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1153, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "participants", "locations": [{"offset": 1271, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1720, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693068, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@2697049"], "journal": "Curr. Biol.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Wright KP", "Linton SK", "Withrow D", "Casiraghi L", "Lanza SM", "Iglesia H", "Vetter C", "Depner CM"]}
{"_id": "32693067|None", "id": "32693067", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Curr. Biol.; 2020 Jul 20 ; 30 (14) 795-. doi:10.1016/j.cub.2020.06.021", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Blume C, Schmidt MH, Cajochen C, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Effects of the COVID-19 lockdown on human sleep and rest-activity rhythms.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 15, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 36, "length": 5}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 75, "text": "In modern societies, human rest-activity rhythms and sleep result from the tensions and dynamics between the conflicting poles of external social time (e.g., work hours and leisure activities) and an individual's internal biological time. A mismatch between the two has been suggested to induce 'social jetlag' [1] and 'social sleep restriction', that is, shifts in sleep timing and differences in sleep duration between work days and free days. Social jetlag [2,3] and sleep restrictions [4] have repeatedly been associated with negative consequences on health, mental wellbeing, and performance. In a large-scale quasi-experimental design, we investigated the effects of the phase with the most rigorous COVID-19 restrictions on the relationship between social and biological rhythms as well as sleep during a six-week period (mid-March until end of April 2020) in three European societies (Austria, Germany, Switzerland). We found that, on one hand, the restrictions reduced the mismatch between external (social) and internal (biological) sleep-wake timing, as indexed by significant reductions in social jetlag and social sleep restriction, with a concomitant increase in sleep duration. Sleep quality on the other hand was slightly reduced. The improved individual sleep-wake timing can presumably be attributed to an increased flexibility of social schedules, for instance due to more work being accomplished from home. However, this unprecedented situation also led to a significant increase in self-perceived burden, which was attendant to the decrease in sleep quality. These adverse effects may be alleviated by exposure to natural daylight as well as physical exercise.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "6", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 96, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 781, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693067, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "Curr. Biol.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Blume C", "Schmidt MH", "Cajochen C"]}
{"_id": "32693039|None", "id": "32693039", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Ann. Thorac. Surg.; 2020 Jul 18 . doi:10.1016/j.athoracsur.2020.07.003", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Luc JGY, Lou X, Brescia A, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Maximizing Cardiothoracic Surgery Training During the COVID-19 Pandemic: The Resident Perspective.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 54, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 99, "text": "", "sentences": [], "annotations": [], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32693039, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "Ann. Thorac. Surg.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Luc JGY", "Lou X", "Brescia A"]}
{"_id": "32693023|None", "id": "32693023", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Alcohol; 2020 Jul 18 . doi:10.1016/j.alcohol.2020.07.006", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Aghababaeian H, Hamdanieh L, Ostadtaghizadeh A, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Alcohol Intake in Attempt to Fight COVID-19: A Medical Myth in Iran.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000438", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "Alcohol", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 35, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 69, "text": "The coronavirus disease (COVID-19) spread rapidly worldwide and led to the death of thousands of people. To date, there isn't any vaccine or specific antiviral medicine that can prevent or treat this virus. This caused panic among citizens who try their best to prevent being infected. In Iran, alcohol poisoning was reported and led to the death of hundreds of people in several provinces. The incident occurred after a rumor circulated in the country that drinking alcohol can cure or prevent being infected by COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 73, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 94, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "death", "locations": [{"offset": 144, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 166, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infected", "locations": [{"