{"_id": "32692934|None", "id": "32692934", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J. Urol.; 2020 Jul 17 101097. doi:10.1097/JU.0000000000001288", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Tachibana I, Ferguson EL, Mahenthiran A, Natarajan JP, Masterson TA, Bahler CD, Sundaram CP, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Delaying Cancer Cases in Urology during COVID-19: Review of the Literature.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D009369", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Cancer", "locations": [{"offset": 9, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 40, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 76, "text": "PURPOSE: Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) is a global pandemic affecting hospital systems and the availability of resources for surgical procedures. Our aim is to provide guidance for urologists to help prioritize urologic cancer surgeries. MATERIAL AND METHODS: We reviewed published literature on bladder cancer, upper tract urothelial carcinoma (UTUC), penile cancer, testis cancer, prostate cancer, renal cancer, and adrenal cancer. RESULTS: For muscle invasive bladder cancer (MIBC), delays should be less than roughly 10 weeks and neoadjuvant chemotherapy should be considered. For non-MIBC, patients should be counseled appropriately based on risk and intravesical therapies can continue. UTUC should also be treated with minimal delays for high risk patients, especially with ureteral tumors. Surgery for T1 renal cancers when indicated can be delayed until adequate resources are available. Patients with T2 renal cancer should be considered for early surgery if there are unfavorable pre-operative characteristics. Higher stage renal tumors should be considered for early surgery. Early multi-disciplinary approach is recommended for metastatic renal cancers. High risk prostate cancer may need preferential treatment and consideration of neoadjuvant hormonal therapy. Penile cancer can have worse sexual or oncologic outcome with prolonged surgical delay. Likewise, adrenal cancer is aggressive and needs early surgical treatment. Testicular cancer should be treated in a timely manner with surgery or chemotherapy, as indicated. CONCLUSIONS: This review should further assist urologists in recognizing patients with potentially aggressive tumor biology that warrant early treatment.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Coronavirus Disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 85, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 111, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D009369", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "cancer", "locations": [{"offset": 302, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D001749", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "bladder cancer", "locations": [{"offset": 378, "length": 14}]}, {"id": "34", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012141", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "upper tract urothelial carcinoma", "locations": [{"offset": 394, "length": 32}]}, {"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D010412", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "penile cancer", "locations": [{"offset": 435, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D013736", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "testis cancer", "locations": [{"offset": 450, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D011471", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "prostate cancer", "locations": [{"offset": 465, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007680", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "renal cancer", "locations": [{"offset": 482, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000310", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "adrenal cancer", "lo