{"_id": "32692801|None", "id": "32692801", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Bioinformatics; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1093/bioinformatics/btaa645", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Kong R, Yang G, Xue R, Liu M, Wang F, Hu J, Guo X, Chang S, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "COVID-19 Docking Server: A meta server for docking small molecules, peptides and antibodies against potential targets of COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 121, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 131, "text": "MOTIVATION: The coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) caused by a new type of coronavirus has been emerging from China and led to thousands of death globally since December 2019. Despite many groups have engaged in studying the newly emerged virus and searching for the treatment of COVID-19, the understanding of the COVID-19 target-ligand interactions represents a key challenge. Herein, we introduce COVID-19 Docking Server, a web server that predicts the binding modes between COVID-19 targets and the ligands including small molecules, peptides and antibodies. RESULTS: Structures of proteins involved in the virus life cycle were collected or constructed based on the homologs of coronavirus, and prepared ready for docking. The meta platform provides a free and interactive tool for the prediction of COVID-19 target-ligand interactions and following drug discovery for COVID-19. AVAILABILITY: http://ncov.schanglab.org.cn. SUPPLEMENTARY INFORMATION: Supplementary data are available at Bioinformatics online.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 147, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 173, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 207, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "death", "locations": [{"offset": 272, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 412, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 447, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 532, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 610, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 815, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 937, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1006, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "ncov", "locations": [{"offset": 1037, "length": 4}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692801, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@2697049", "species@11118", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643"], "journal": "Bioinformatics", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Kong R", "Yang G", "Xue R", "Liu M", "Wang F", "Hu J", "Guo X", "Chang S"]}
{"_id": "32692769|None", "id": "32692769", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "PLoS ONE; 2020 ; 15 (7) 0236312. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0236312", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Dargent A, Chatelain E, Kreitmann L, Quenot JP, Cour M, Argaud L, COVID-LUS study group, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Lung ultrasound score to monitor COVID-19 pneumonia progression in patients with ARDS.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19 pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 33, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 67, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012128", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "ARDS", "locations": [{"offset": 81, "length": 4}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 87, "text": "COVID-19 pneumonia typically begins with subpleural ground glass opacities with progressive extension on computerized tomography studies. Lung ultrasound is well suited to this interstitial, subpleural involvement, and it is now broadly used in intensive care units (ICUs). The extension and severity of lung infiltrates can be described numerically with a reproducible and validated lung ultrasound score (LUSS). We hypothesized that LUSS might be useful as a tool to non-invasively monitor the evolution of COVID-19 pneumonia at the bedside. LUSS monitoring was rapidly implemented in the management of our COVID-19 patients with RT-PCR-documented COVID-19. The LUSS was evaluated repeatedly at the bedside. We present a graphic description of the course of LUSS during COVID-19 in 10 consecutive patients admitted in our intensive care unit with moderate to severe ARDS between March 15 and 30th. LUSS appeared to be closely related to the disease progression. In successfully extubated patients, LUSS decreased and was lower than at the time of intubation. LUSS increased inexorably in a patient who died from refractory hypoxemia. LUSS helped with the diagnosis of ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP), showing an increased score and the presence of new lung consolidations in all 5 patients with VAPs. There was also a good agreement between CT-scans and LUSS as for the presence of lung consolidations. In conclusion, our early experience suggests that LUSS monitoring accurately reflect disease progression and indicates potential usefulness for the management of COVID-19 patients with ARDS. It might help with early VAP diagnosis, mechanical ventilation weaning management, and potentially reduce the need for X-ray and CT exams. LUSS evaluation is easy to use and readily available in ICUs throughout the world, and might be a safe, cheap and simple tool to optimize critically ill COVID-19 patients care during the pandemic.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19 pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 87, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19 pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 596, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 696, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 705, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 737, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 859, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 886, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012128", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "ARDS", "locations": [{"offset": 955, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1077, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "34", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patient", "locations": [{"offset": 1179, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000860", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "refractory hypoxemia", "locations": [{"offset": 1201, "length": 20}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D011014", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 1279, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1376, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1660, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1669, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "40", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012128", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "ARDS", "locations": [{"offset": 1683, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "41", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D016638", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "critically ill", "locations": [{"offset": 1966, "length": 14}]}, {"id": "42", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1981, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "43", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1990, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692769, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D016638", "disease@MESH:D012128", "species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D000860", "disease@MESH:D011014"], "journal": "PLoS ONE", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Dargent A", "Chatelain E", "Kreitmann L", "Quenot JP", "Cour M", "Argaud L", "COVID-LUS study group"]}
{"_id": "32692757|None", "id": "32692757", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "PLoS ONE; 2020 ; 15 (7) 0236307. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0236307", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Fry CV, Cai X, Zhang Y, Wagner CS, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Consolidation in a crisis: Patterns of international collaboration in early COVID-19 research.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 76, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 95, "text": "This paper seeks to understand whether a catastrophic and urgent event, such as the first months of the COVID-19 pandemic, accelerates or reverses trends in international collaboration, especially in and between China and the United States. A review of research articles produced in the first months of the COVID-19 pandemic shows that COVID-19 research had smaller teams and involved fewer nations than pre-COVID-19 coronavirus research. The United States and China were, and continue to be in the pandemic era, at the center of the global network in coronavirus related research, while developing countries are relatively absent from early research activities in the COVID-19 period. Not only are China and the United States at the center of the global network of coronavirus research, but they strengthen their bilateral research relationship during COVID-19, producing more than 4.9% of all global articles together, in contrast to 3.6% before the pandemic. In addition, in the COVID-19 period, joined by the United Kingdom, China and the United States continued their roles as the largest contributors to, and home to the main funders of, coronavirus related research. These findings suggest that the global COVID-19 pandemic shifted the geographic loci of coronavirus research, as well as the structure of scientific teams, narrowing team membership and favoring elite structures. These findings raise further questions over the decisions that scientists face in the formation of teams to maximize a speed, skill trade-off. Policy implications are discussed.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 199, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 402, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 431, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "COVID-19 coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 503, "length": 20}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 647, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 764, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 861, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 948, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1077, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 1239, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1308, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 1357, "length": 11}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692757, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@11118", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@2697049"], "journal": "PLoS ONE", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Fry CV", "Cai X", "Zhang Y", "Wagner CS"]}
{"_id": "32692753|None", "id": "32692753", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "PLoS ONE; 2020 ; 15 (7) 0236464. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0236464", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Hong HG, Li Y, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Estimation of time-varying reproduction numbers underlying epidemiological processes: A new statistical tool for the COVID-19 pandemic.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 117, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 136, "text": "The coronavirus pandemic has rapidly evolved into an unprecedented crisis. The susceptible-infectious-removed (SIR) model and its variants have been used for modeling the pandemic. However, time-independent parameters in the classical models may not capture the dynamic transmission and removal processes, governed by virus containment strategies taken at various phases of the epidemic. Moreover, few models account for possible inaccuracies of the reported cases. We propose a Poisson model with time-dependent transmission and removal rates to account for possible random errors in reporting and estimate a time-dependent disease reproduction number, which may reflect the effectiveness of virus control strategies. We apply our method to study the pandemic in several severely impacted countries, and analyze and forecast the evolving spread of the coronavirus. We have developed an interactive web application to facilitate readers' use of our method.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 140, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 989, "length": 11}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692753, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@11118", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "PLoS ONE", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Hong HG", "Li Y"]}
{"_id": "32692743|None", "id": "32692743", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "PLoS Med.; 2020 Jul ; 17 (7) 1003240. doi:10.1371/journal.pmed.1003240", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Zhang L, Tao Y, Shen M, Fairley CK, Guo Y, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Can self-imposed prevention measures mitigate the COVID-19 epidemic?", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 50, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 69, "text": "Yuming Guo and colleagues discuss the research by Teslya et al that highlights the importance of personal preventative measures in avoiding a second wave of the COVID-19 epidemic.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 230, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692743, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "PLoS Med.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Zhang L", "Tao Y", "Shen M", "Fairley CK", "Guo Y"]}
{"_id": "32692736|None", "id": "32692736", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "PLoS Med.; 2020 Jul ; 17 (7) 1003166. doi:10.1371/journal.pmed.1003166", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Teslya A, Pham TM, Godijk NG, Kretzschmar ME, Bootsma MCJ, Rozhnova G, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Impact of self-imposed prevention measures and short-term government-imposed social distancing on mitigating and delaying a COVID-19 epidemic: A modelling study.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 124, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 162, "text": "BACKGROUND: The coronavirus disease (COVID-19) caused by the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) has spread to nearly every country in the world since it first emerged in China in December 2019. Many countries have implemented social distancing as a measure to \"flatten the curve\" of the ongoing epidemics. Evaluation of the impact of government-imposed social distancing and of other measures to control further spread of COVID-19 is urgent, especially because of the large societal and economic impact of the former. The aim of this study was to compare the individual and combined effectiveness of self-imposed prevention measures and of short-term government-imposed social distancing in mitigating, delaying, or preventing a COVID-19 epidemic. METHODS AND FINDINGS: We developed a deterministic compartmental transmission model of SARS-CoV-2 in a population stratified by disease status (susceptible, exposed, infectious with mild or severe disease, diagnosed, and recovered) and disease awareness status (aware and unaware) due to the spread of COVID-19. Self-imposed measures were assumed to be taken by disease-aware individuals and included handwashing, mask-wearing, and social distancing. Government-imposed social distancing reduced the contact rate of individuals irrespective of their disease or awareness status. The model was parameterized using current best estimates of key epidemiological parameters from COVID-19 clinical studies. The model outcomes included the peak number of diagnoses, attack rate, and time until the peak number of diagnoses. For fast awareness spread in the population, self-imposed measures can significantly reduce the attack rate and diminish and postpone the peak number of diagnoses. We estimate that a large epidemic can be prevented if the efficacy of these measures exceeds 50%. For slow awareness spread, self-imposed measures reduce the peak number of diagnoses and attack rate but do not affect the timing of the peak. Early implementation of short-term government-imposed social distancing alone is estimated to delay (by at most 7 months for a 3-month intervention) but not to reduce the peak. The delay can be even longer and the height of the peak can be additionally reduced if this intervention is combined with self-imposed measures that are continued after government-imposed social distancing has been lifted. Our analyses are limited in that they do not account for stochasticity, demographics, heterogeneities in contact patterns or mixing, spatial effects, imperfect isolation of individuals with severe disease, and reinfection with COVID-19. CONCLUSIONS: Our results suggest that information dissemination about COVID-19, which causes individual adoption of handwashing, mask-wearing, and social distancing, can be an effective strategy to mitigate and delay the epidemic. Early initiated short-term government-imposed social distancing can buy time for healthcare systems to prepare for an increasing COVID-19 burden. We stress the importance of disease awareness in controlling the ongoing epidemic and recommend that, in addition to policies on social distancing, governments and public health institutions mobilize people to adopt self-imposed measures with proven efficacy in order to successfully tackle COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 178, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 199, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2", "locations": [{"offset": 223, "length": 47}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 272, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 610, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 917, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 1023, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1238, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1611, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 2786, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 2866, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 3156, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 3373, "length": 6}]}, 