{"_id": "32692584|None", "id": "32692584", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Am J Speech Lang Pathol; 2020 Jul 17 1-16. doi:10.1044/2020_AJSLP-20-00096", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Namasivayam-MacDonald AM, Riquelme LF, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Speech-Language Pathology Management for Adults With COVID-19 in the Acute Hospital Setting: Initial Recommendations to Guide Clinical Practice.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 53, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 145, "text": "Purpose This document outlines initial recommendations for speech-language pathology management of adult patients with COVID-19 in the acute hospital setting. Method The authors initially developed these recommendations by adapting those developed for physical therapists working with patients with COVID-19 by Thomas et al. (2020). The recommendations then underwent review by 14 speech-language pathologists and rehabilitation-focused academics representing seven countries (Belgium, Brazil, Canada, Ireland, Japan, New Zealand, the United States). The authors consolidated and reviewed the feedback in order to decide what should be included or modified. Applicability to a global audience was intended throughout the document. Results The authors had 100% agreement on the elements of the recommendations that needed to be changed/modified or added. The final document includes recommendations for speech-language pathology workforce planning and preparation, caseload management, service delivery and documentation, as well as recommendations for the selection of appropriate personal protective equipment and augmentative and alternative communication equipment in the acute care hospital setting. Conclusions Speech-language pathologists play a critical role in the assessment, management, and treatment of patients with COVID-19. Several important considerations need to be made in order to meet the needs of this unique patient population. As more is learned about the impact of the virus on swallowing and communication, the role of the speech-language pathologist on interdisciplinary care teams will remain paramount.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "9", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 250, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 264, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 430, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 444, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1459, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1473, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patient", "locations": [{"offset": 1574, "length": 7}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692584, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "Am J Speech Lang Pathol", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Namasivayam-MacDonald AM", "Riquelme LF"]}
{"_id": "32692580|None", "id": "32692580", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Ann Am Thorac Soc; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1513/AnnalsATS.202005-566FR", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Farne H, Kumar K, Ritchie AI, Finney LJ, Johnston SL, Singanayagam A, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Repurposing Existing Drugs for the Treatment of COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 48, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 58, "text": "The rapid global spread and significant mortality associated with the coronavirus disease (COVID-19) caused by SARS-CoV-2 viral infection has spurred an urgent race to find effective treatments. Repurposing existing drugs is a particularly attractive approach as pharmacokinetic and safety data already exist, thus development can leapfrog straight to clinical trials of efficacy, generating results far more quickly than de novo drug development. This review summarizes the state of play for the principle drugs identified as candidates to be repurposed for treating COVID-19 grouped by broad mechanism of action: antiviral, immune enhancing, and anti-inflammatory or immunomodulatory. Patient selection, particularly with regard to disease stage, is likely to be key. To date only dexamethasone and remedesivir have been shown to be effective, but several other promising candidates are in trials.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 98, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 128, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 149, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 169, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 186, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 626, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Patient", "locations": [{"offset": 745, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003907", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "dexamethasone", "locations": [{"offset": 841, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "remedesivir", "locations": [{"offset": 859, "length": 11}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692580, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D018352", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643", "species@9606", "chemical@MESH:D003907", "chemical@-", "species@2697049", "disease@MESH:D007239"], "journal": "Ann Am Thorac Soc", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Farne H", "Kumar K", "Ritchie AI", "Finney LJ", "Johnston SL", "Singanayagam A"]}
{"_id": "32692492|None", "id": "32692492", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Isr. Med. Assoc. J.; 2020 Jul ; 7 (22) 335-337", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "David P, Shoenfeld Y, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "The Smell in COVID-19 Infection: Diagnostic Opportunities.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19 Infection", "locations": [{"offset": 13, "length": 18}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 59, "text": "BACKGROUND: There is a high prevalence of olfaction changes, especially in the early presentation, in COVID-19 patients. The mechanisms through which the virus leads to anosmia/hyposmia is still not fully understood. However, olfaction changes could be used as an indication for testing or quarantine. Screening for infections and other diseases by recognizing volatile organic compounds (VOCs) has been previously conducted. Hence, if the coronavirus infection also results in VOCs excretion, physicians could \"smell\" the virus by using electronic noses. We conducted a literature review on olfaction changes and the COVID-19. Our results suggest that these changes could be used an indication for early testing, even as an isolated symptom. We propose that the electronic nose be used as a future screening tool, especially in agglomeration spaces such as airports, for screening for the COVID-19 infection.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 161, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 170, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000857", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "anosmia/hyposmia", "locations": [{"offset": 228, "length": 16}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infections", "locations": [{"offset": 375, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus infection", "locations": [{"offset": 499, "length": 21}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D011507", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "VOCs excretion", "locations": [{"offset": 537, "length": 14}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 677, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 949, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 958, "length": 9}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692492, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D018352", "disease@MESH:D011507", "species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D007239", "disease@MESH:D000857"], "journal": "Isr. Med. Assoc. J.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["David P", "Shoenfeld Y"]}
{"_id": "32692465|None", "id": "32692465", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "FEBS J.; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1111/febs.15491", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Li W, Li M, Ou G, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "COVID-19, Cilia, and Smell.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 28, "text": "The novel coronavirus SARS-CoV-2 is the causative agent of the global COVID-19 outbreak. In addition to pneumonia, other COVID-19-associated symptoms have been reported, including loss of smell (anosmia). However, the connection between infection with coronavirus and anosmia remains enigmatic. It has been reported that defects in olfactory cilia lead to anosmia. In this Viewpoint, we summarize transmission electron microscopic studies of cilia in virus-infected cells. In the human nasal epithelium, coronavirus infects the ciliated cells and causes deciliation. Research has shown that viruses such as Influenza and Sendai attach to the ciliary membrane. The Sendai virus enters cilia by fusing its viral membrane with the ciliary membrane. A recent study on SARS-CoV-2-human protein-protein interactions revealed that the viral non-structural protein Nsp13 interacts with the centrosome components, providing a potential molecular link. The mucociliary escalator removes inhaled pathogenic particles and functions as the first line of protection mechanism against viral infection in the human airway. Thus, future investigation into the virus-cilium interface will help further the battle against COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "novel coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 32, "length": 17}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 50, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 98, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D011014", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 132, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 149, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000857", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "anosmia", "locations": [{"offset": 223, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 265, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 280, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000857", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "anosmia", "locations": [{"offset": 296, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000857", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "anosmia", "locations": [{"offset": 384, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D001102", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "virus-infected", "locations": [{"offset": 479, "length": 14}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 508, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 532, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "34", "infons": {"identifier": "11191", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Sendai virus", "locations": [{"offset": 692, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 792, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 803, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D001102", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "viral infection", "locations": [{"offset": 1098, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 1121, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1231, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32692465, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@9606", "species@11191", "disease@MESH:D011014", "species@2697049", "disease@MESH:D001102", "disease@MESH:D007239", "species@11118", "disease@MESH:D000857"], "journal": "FEBS J.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Li W", "Li M", "Ou G"]}
{"_id": "32692464|None", "id": "32692464", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Hepatology; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1002/hep.31472", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Kovalic AJ, Huang G, Thuluvath PJ, Satapathy SK, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Elevated Liver Biochemistries in Hospitalized Chinese Patients with Severe COVID-19: Systematic Review and Meta-analysis.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Patients", "locations": [{"offset": 54, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 75, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 122, "text": "BACKGROUND & AIMS: Several recent studies have reported an abnormal liver chemistry profile among patients with coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19), although its clinical significance remains unknown. APPROACH & RESULTS: This novel systematic review and meta-analysis identified six studies of 586 patients delineating liver chemistries among patients with severe/critical illness versus mild cases of COVID-19 infection. Patients with severe/critical illness with COVID-19 infection have increased prevalence of coronary artery disease (CAD), cerebrovascular disease, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) as compared to mild cases. A significant association between severe/critical COVID-19 infections with elevations in aspartate aminotransferase (AST) (pooled mean difference [MD], 11.70 U/L; 95% confidence interval [CI], 2.97, 20.43; P = 0.009), elevated total bilirubin (pooled MD, 0.14 mg/dL; 95% CI, 0.06, 0.22; P = 0.0005), and decreased albumin (pooled MD, -0.68 g/L; 95% CI, -0.81, -0.55; P < 0.00001) was noted. There was also a trend toward elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) levels among these severe cases (pooled MD, 8.84 U/L; 95% CI, -2.28, 19.97; P = 0.12); however, this did not reach statistical significance. More severe/critically ill cases were associated with leukocytosis, neutrophilia, lymphopenia, elevated creatinine kinase, elevated lactate dehydrogenase (LDH), and elevated prothrombin time (PT). CONCLUSIONS: Comorbidities, including CAD, cerebrovascular disease, and COPD, are more prevalent in hospitalized Chinese patients with severe/critical illness from COVID-19, and these patients are more likely to manifest with abnormal liver chemistries. Further prospective studies are crucial to understand the pathophysiologic mechanisms underlying the hepatic manifestations of the novel COVID-19 infection and its clinical significance.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 220, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 234, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 260, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "40", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 420, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "41", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 465, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "42", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 524, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "43", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 533, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "44", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Patients", "locations": [{"offset": 544, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "45", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 587, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "46"