{"_id": "32692185|None", "id": "32692185", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J. Proteome Res.; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1021/acs.jproteome.0c00392", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Chien M, Anderson TK, Jockusch S, Tao C, Li X, Kumar S, Russo JJ, Kirchdoerfer RN, Ju J, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Nucleotide Analogues as Inhibitors of SARS-CoV-2 Polymerase, a Key Drug Target for COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 38, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 83, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 93, "text": "SARS-CoV-2 is responsible for the current COVID-19 pandemic. Based on our analysis of hepatitis C virus and coronavirus replication, and the molecular structures and activities of viral inhibitors, we previously demonstrated that three nucleotide analogues (the triphosphates of Sofosbuvir, Alovudine and AZT) inhibit the SARS-CoV RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (RdRp). We also demonstrated that a library of additional nucleotide analogues terminate RNA synthesis catalyzed by the SARS-CoV-2 RdRp, a well-established drug target for COVID-19. Here, we used polymerase extension experiments to demonstrate that the active triphosphate form of Sofosbuvir (an FDA-approved hepatitis C drug), is incorporated by SARS-CoV-2 RdRp, and blocks further incorporation. Using the molecular insight gained from the previous studies, we selected the active triphosphate forms of six other anti-viral agents, Alovudine, Tenofovir alafenamide, AZT, Abacavir, Lamivudine and Emtricitabine, for evaluation as inhibitors of the SARS-CoV-2 RdRp, and demonstrated the ability of these viral polymerase inhibitors to be incorporated by SARS-CoV-2 RdRp, where they terminate further polymerase extension with varying efficiency. These results provide a molecular basis for inhibition of the SARS-CoV-2 RdRp by these nucleotide analogues. If sufficient efficacy of some of these FDA-approved drugs in inhibiting viral replication in cell culture is established, they may be explored as potential COVID-19 therapeutics.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 93, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 135, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "11103", "type": "Species"}, "text": "hepatitis C virus", "locations": [{"offset": 179, "length": 17}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 201, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C005692", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "triphosphates", "locations": [{"offset": 355, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "40", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000069474", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "Sofosbuvir", "locations": [{"offset": 372, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "41", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C002854", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "Alovudine", "locations": [{"offset": 384, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "42", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D015215", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "AZT", "locations": [{"offset": 398, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "43", "infons": {"identifier": "694009", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV", "locations": [{"offset": 415, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "44", "infons": {"identifier": "43740578", "type": "Gene"}, "text": "RdRp", "locations": [{"offset": 454, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "45", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 573, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "46", "infons": {"identifier": "43740578", "type": "Gene"}, "text": "RdRp", "location