{"_id": "32691877|None", "id": "32691877", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J. Med. Virol.; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1002/jmv.26325", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Hoang T, Thi Anh TT, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Ambient Air Pollution, Meteorology, and COVID-19 Infection in Korea.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 40, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Infection", "locations": [{"offset": 49, "length": 9}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 69, "text": "BACKGROUND: The outbreak of novel pneumonia coronavirus disease has become a public health concern worldwide. Here, for the first time, the association between Korean meteorological factors and air pollutants and the COVID-19 infection was investigated. MATERIALS AND METHODS: Data of air pollutants, meteorological factors, and daily COVID-19 confirmed cases of 7 metropolitan cities and 9 provinces were obtained from February 03, 2020 to May 05, 2020 during the first wave of pandemic across Korea. We applied the generalized additive model to investigate the temporal relationship. RESULTS: There was a significantly non-linear association between daily temperature and COVID-19 confirmed cases. Each 1o C increase in temperature was associated with 9% (lag 0-14, OR=1.09, 95% CI=1.03-1.15) increase of COVID-19 confirmed cases when the temperature was below 8o C. A 0.01 ppm increase in NO2 (lag 0-7, lag 0.14, and lag 0-21) was significantly associated with increases of COVID-19 confirmed cases, with ORs (95% CIs) of 1.13 (1.02-1.25), 1.19 (1.09-1.30), and 1.30 (1.19-1.41), respectively. A 0.1 ppm increase in CO (lag 0-21) was associated with the increase in COVID-19 confirmed cases (OR=1.10, 95% CI=1.04-1.16). There was a positive association between per 0.001 ppm of SO2 concentration (lag 0, lag 0-7, and lag 0-14) and COVID-19 confirmed cases, with ORs (95% CIs) of 1.13 (1.04-1.22), 1.20 (1.11-1.31), and 1.15 (1.07-1.25), respectively. CONCLUSION: There were significantly temporal associations between temperature, NO2 , CO, and SO2 concentrations and daily COVID-19 confirmed cases in Korea. This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "pneumonia coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 103, "length": 29}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 286, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 295, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 404, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 743, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 876, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1046, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1238, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D013458", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "SO2", "locations": [{"offset": 1350, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1403, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "NO2", "locations": [{"offset": 1603, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D002248", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "CO", "locations": [{"offset": 1609, "length": 2}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D013458", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "SO2", "locations": [{"offset": 1617, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1646, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691877, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D018352", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "chemical@MESH:D013458", "chemical@-", "disease@MESH:D007239", "chemical@MESH:D002248"], "journal": "J. Med. Virol.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Hoang T", "Thi Anh TT"]}
{"_id": "32691875|None", "id": "32691875", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J. Med. Virol.; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1002/jmv.26320", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Wang Y, Wang L, Cao H, Liu C, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "SARS-CoV-2 S1 is superior to the RBD as a COVID-19 subunit vaccine antigen.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 42, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 76, "text": "Since its emergence in December 2019, severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) has developed into a global pandemic within a matter of months. While subunit vaccines are one of the prominent options for combating coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19), the immunogenicity of spike protein-based antigens remains unknown. When immunized in mice, the S1 domain induced much higher IgG and IgA antibody levels than the RBD and more efficiently neutralized SARS-CoV-2 when adjuvanted with alum. It is inferred that a large proportion of these neutralization epitopes are located in the S1 domain but outside the RBD and that some of these are spatial epitopes. This finding indicates that expression systems with posttranslational modification abilities are important to maintain the natural configurations of recombinant spike protein antigens and are critical for effective COVID-19 vaccines. Further, adjuvants prone to a Th1 response should be considered for S1-based subunit COVID-19 vaccines to reduce the potential risk of antibody-dependent enhancement (ADE) of infection. This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2", "locations": [{"offset": 114, "length": 47}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 163, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 309, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 335, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "10090", "type": "Species"}, "text": "mice", "locations": [{"offset": 432, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 546, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C041524", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "alum", "locations": [{"offset": 578, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 965, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1069, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 1159, "length": 9}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691875, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@10090", "species@2697049", "disease@MESH:D007239", "chemical@MESH:C041524"], "journal": "J. Med. Virol.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Wang Y", "Wang L", "Cao H", "Liu C"]}
{"_id": "32691863|None", "id": "32691863", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Eur. J. Clin. Invest.; 2020 Jul 21 13357. doi:10.1111/eci.13357", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Andrey DO, Cohen P, Meyer B, Torriani G, Yerly S, Mazza L, Calame A, Arm-Vernez I, Guessous I, Stringhini S, Roux-Lombard P, Fontao L, Agoritsas T, Stirnemann J, Reny JL, Siegrist CA, Eckerle I, Kaiser L, Vuilleumier N, Geneva Center for Emerging Viral Diseases, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Diagnostic accuracy of Augurix COVID-19 IgG serology rapid test.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 31, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 65, "text": "AIMS: To validate the diagnostic accuracy of the Augurix SARS-CoV-2 IgM/IgG rapid immunoassay diagnostic test (RDT) for COVID-19. METHODS: In this unmatched 1:1 case-control study, blood samples from 46 real-time RT-PCR-confirmed SARS-CoV-2 hospitalized cases and 45 healthy donors (negative controls) were studied. Diagnostic accuracy of the IgG RDT was assessed against both an in-house recombinant spike-expressing immunofluorescence assay (rIFA), as an established reference method (primary endpoint), and the Euroimmun SARS-CoV2 IgG enzyme-linked immunosorbent assays (ELISA) (secondary endpoint). RESULTS: COVID-19 patients were more likely to be male (61% versus 20%; p=0.0001) and older (median 66 versus 47 years-old; p<0.001) than controls. Whole blood IgG-RDT results showed 86% and 93% overall Kendall concordance with rIFA and IgG ELISA, respectively. IgG RDT performances were similar between plasma and whole blood. Overall, RDT sensitivity was 88% (95% confidence interval [95%CI]: 70-96), specificity 98% (95%CI: 90-100), PPV 97% (95%CI: 80-100) and NPV 94% (95%CI: 84-98). The IgG-RDT carried out from 0 to 6 days, 7 to 14 days and >14 days after the SARS-CoV-2 RT-PCR test displayed 30%, 73% and 100% positivity rates in the COVID-19 group, respectively. When considering samples taken >14 days after RT-PCR diagnosis, NPV was 100% (95%CI:90-100), and PPV was 100% (95%CI:72-100). CONCLUSIONS: The Augurix IgG-RDT done in whole blood displays a high diagnostic accuracy for SARS-CoV-2 IgG in high COVID-19 prevalence settings, where its use could be considered in the absence of routine diagnostic serology facilities.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 122, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 185, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 295, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV2", "locations": [{"offset": 589, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 677, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 686, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 1234, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1309, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "-", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "Augurix", "locations": [{"offset": 1482, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 1558, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1581, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691863, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "chemical@-", "species@2697049"], "journal": "Eur. J. Clin. Invest.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Andrey DO", "Cohen P", "Meyer B", "Torriani G", "Yerly S", "Mazza L", "Calame A", "Arm-Vernez I", "Guessous I", "Stringhini S", "Roux-Lombard P", "Fontao L", "Agoritsas T", "Stirnemann J", "Reny JL", "Siegrist CA", "Eckerle I", "Kaiser L", "Vuilleumier N", "Geneva Center for Emerging Viral Diseases"]}
{"_id": "32691856|None", "id": "32691856", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J Ultrasound Med; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1002/jum.15389", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Rosado-Mendez IM, Smargiassi A, Inchingolo R, Soldati G, Muller M, Demi L, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Lung Ultrasound for Treatment of Patients With COVID-19: Please Report Your Settings and Mechanical Index.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Patients", "locations": [{"offset": 33, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 47, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 107, "text": "", "sentences": [], "annotations": [], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691856, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@9606"], "journal": "J Ultrasound Med", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Rosado-Mendez IM", "Smargiassi A", "Inchingolo R", "Soldati G", "Muller M", "Demi L"]}
{"_id": "32691843|None", "id": "32691843", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J. Infect. Dis.; 2020 Jul 21 . doi:10.1093/infdis/jiaa436", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Li Y, Wang X, Nair H, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Global seasonality of human seasonal coronaviruses: a clue for post-pandemic circulating season of SARS-CoV-2 virus?", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 22, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronaviruses", "locations": [{"offset": 37, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 99, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 117, "text": "BACKGROUND: The ongoing pandemic of Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) caused by SARS-CoV-2 virus could recur as seasonal outbreaks, a circulating pattern observed among other pre-existing human seasonal coronaviruses (sCoV). However, little is known about seasonality of sCoV on a global scale. METHODS: We conducted a systematic review of data on seasonality of sCoV. We compared seasonality of sCoV with influenza virus and respiratory syncytial virus. We modelled monthly activity of sCoV using site-specific weather data. RESULTS: We included sCoV seasonality data in 40 sites from 21 countries. SCoV was prevalent in winter months in most temperate sites except for China while sCoV tended to be less seasonal in China and in tropical sites. In temperate sites excluding China, 53.1% of annual sCoV cases (Interquartile range, IQR: 34.6-61.9) occurred during influenza season and 49.6% (IQR: 30.2-60.2) of sCoV occurred during respiratory syncytial virus season. Low temperature combined with high relative humidity was associated with higher sCoV activity. CONCLUSIONS: This is the first study that provides an overview of the global seasonality of sCoV. Our findings offer clues to the possible post-pandemic circulating season of SARS-CoV-2 and add to the knowledge pool necessary for post-pandemic preparedness for SARS-CoV-2.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Coronavirus disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 153, "length": 24}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 179, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 199, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 307, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronaviruses", "locations": [{"offset": 322, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "11309", "type": "Species"}, "text": "influenza virus", "locations": [{"offset": 525, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "12814", "type": "Species"}, "text": "respiratory syncytial virus", "locations": [{"offset": 545, "length": 27}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "11309", "type": "Species"}, "text": "influenza", "locations": [{"offset": 983, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "12814", "type": "Species"}, "text": "respiratory syncytial virus", "locations": [{"offset": 1051, "length": 27}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 1357, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 1443, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691843, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@11309", "