{"_id": "32691359|None", "id": "32691359", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Matern Child Health J; 2020 Jul 20 . doi:10.1007/s10995-020-02982-8", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Marshall J, Kihlstr\u00f6m L, Buro A, Chandran V, Prieto C, Stein-Elger R, Koeut-Futch K, Parish A, Hood K, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Statewide Implementation of Virtual Perinatal Home Visiting During COVID-19.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 67, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 77, "text": "PURPOSE: This evaluation describes efforts taken by MIECHV administrators and staff during the pandemic using data collected from 60 MIECHV staff surveys and nine statewide weekly focus groups. DESCRIPTION: The Florida Maternal, Infant and Early Childhood Home Visiting (MIECHV) Initiative funds perinatal home visiting for pregnant women and families with infants throughout the state. Florida MIECHV has shown resilience to disasters and times of crises in the past, while generating a culture of adaptation and continuous quality improvement among local implementing agencies. Florida MIECHV responded to the COVID-19 pandemic crisis within the first few days of the first reported case in Florida by providing guidance on virtual home visits and working remotely. ASSESSMENT: Findings highlight the role of administrative leadership and communication, staff willingness/morale, logistical considerations, and the needs of enrolled families who face hardships during the pandemic such as job loss, limited supplies, food insecurity, technology limitations, and stress. Home visitors support enrolled families by connecting them with resources, providing public health education and delivering evidence-based home visiting curricula virtually. They also recognized the emotional burden surrounding COVID-19 impacts and uncertainties along with achieving work-life balance by caring for their own children. CONCLUSION: This evaluation helped in understanding the impact of the pandemic on this maternal and child health program and fundamentals of transition to virtual home visiting services. Virtual home visiting appears to be feasible and provides an essential connection to supports for families who may not otherwise have the means or knowledge to access them.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "women", "locations": [{"offset": 410, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "infants", "locations": [{"offset": 434, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 689, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007589", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "job loss", "locations": [{"offset": 1068, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000079225", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "stress", "locations": [{"offset": 1141, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1377, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "children", "locations": [{"offset": 1475, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "child", "locations": [{"offset": 1585, "length": 5}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691359, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:D007589", "disease@MESH:D000079225", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "Matern Child Health J", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Marshall J", "Kihlstr\u00f6m L", "Buro A", "Chandran V", "Prieto C", "Stein-Elger R", "Koeut-Futch K", "Parish A", "Hood K"]}
{"_id": "32691351|None", "id": "32691351", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J Robot Surg; 2020 Jul 20 . doi:10.1007/s11701-020-01120-4", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Moawad GN, Rahman S, Martino MA, Klebanoff JS, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Robotic surgery during the COVID pandemic: why now and why for the future.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID", "locations": [{"offset": 27, "length": 5}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 75, "text": "Health care has changed in unprecedented ways since the first reported cases of COVID-19. With global case rates continuing to rise and government restrictions beginning to loosen, many worry that a second wave in our future. In many hospitals around the world, non-emergent surgeries were put on hold as hospitals were transformed into COVID centers. As surgeons and administrators do their best to reinstate non-emergent procedures, guidance is sought from any and all reliable sources. Robotic surgery has many known and demonstrated benefits over open surgery and often over conventional laparoscopy. In this commentary, we aim to highlight some of the advantages robotic surgery may offer during this uniquely challenging time in health care.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 155, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID", "locations": [{"offset": 412, "length": 5}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691351, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "J Robot Surg", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Moawad GN", "Rahman S", "Martino MA", "Klebanoff JS"]}
{"_id": "32691342|None", "id": "32691342", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J. Nephrol.; 2020 Jul 20 . doi:10.1007/s40620-020-00789-y", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Farouk SS, Fiaccadori E, Cravedi P, Campbell KN, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "COVID-19 and the kidney: what we think we know so far and what we don't.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 73, "text": "The novel coronavirus disease infection (COVID-19) outbreak that was declared a global pandemic in March 2020 had led to an internationally variable but concerning incidence of COVID-associated acute kidney injury (AKI), with prevalence reported as high as 46% in large cohorts of hospitalized patients. Variability in AKI may be explained by differences in traditional risk factors for AKI, heterogeneity among patient cohorts, and differences in racial and ethnic groups. Further, AKI requiring kidney replacement therapies (KRT) has been associated with increased mortality. Proposed mechanisms of kidney injury include direct viral-induced tubular or glomerular injury, sepsis-associated AKI, and thrombotic disease. Kidney pathology include acute tubular injury, glomerular fibrin thrombi, pigmented tubular casts, and collapsing focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. \"Viral-like\" particles have been observed in renal samples at electron microscopy and viral RNA has been identified in both glomerular and tubular compartments of kidney specimens, but the link between viral presence and injury remain unclear. Though the link between AKI and poor outcomes is clear, prevalence and outcomes of COVID-19 in patients with chronic kidney disease and end stage kidney disease has not yet been reported. In patients on immunosuppression like those with kidney transplants or glomerular disease, COVID-19 has presented a management dilemma. Herein, we review the existing literature on kidney disease in COVID-19 and discuss what remains to be learned.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "novel coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 77, "length": 25}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 103, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 114, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID", "locations": [{"offset": 250, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D058186", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "acute kidney injury", "locations": [{"offset": 267, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 367, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patient", "locations": [{"offset": 485, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "34", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 640, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D058186", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "kidney injury", "locations": [{"offset": 674, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007674", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "glomerular injury", "locations": [{"offset": 728, "length": 17}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018805", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "sepsis", "locations": [{"offset": 747, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D013927", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "thrombotic disease", "locations": [{"offset": 774, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D00