{"_id": "32691016|None", "id": "32691016", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Infect Dis Model; 2020 ; 5 442-458. doi:10.1016/j.idm.2020.06.006", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7342051", "type": "title", "authors": "Killeen GF, Kiware SS, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Why lockdown? Why national unity? Why global solidarity? Simplified arithmetic tools for decision-makers, health professionals, journalists and the general public to explore containment options for the 2019 novel coronavirus.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "2019 novel coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 202, "length": 22}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 226, "text": "As every country in the world struggles with the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, it is essential that as many people as possible understand the epidemic containment, elimination and exclusion strategies required to tackle it. Simplified arithmetic models of COVID-19 transmission, control and elimination are presented in user-friendly Shiny and Excel formats that allow non-specialists to explore, query, critique and understand the containment decisions facing their country and the world at large. Although the predictive model is broadly applicable, the simulations presented are based on parameter values representative of the United Republic of Tanzania, which is still early enough in its epidemic cycle and response to avert a national catastrophe. The predictions of these models illustrate (1) why ambitious lock-down interventions to crush the curve represent the only realistic way for individual countries to contain their national-level epidemics before they turn into outright catastrophes, (2) why these need to be implemented so early, so stringently and for such extended periods, (3) why high prevalence of other pathogens causing similar symptoms to mild COVID-19 precludes the use of contact tracing as a substitute for lock down interventions to contain and eliminate epidemics, (4) why partial containment strategies intended to merely flatten the curve, by maintaining epidemics at manageably low levels, are grossly unrealistic, and (5) why local elimination may only be sustained after lock down ends if imported cases are comprehensively excluded, so international co-operation to conditionally re-open trade and travel between countries certified as free of COVID-19 represents the best strategy for motivating progress towards pandemic eradication at global level. The three sequential goals that every country needs to emphatically embrace are contain, eliminate and exclude. As recently emphasized by the World Health Organization, success will require widespread genuine national unity and unprecedented global solidarity.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 283, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "8", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 331, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "9", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 479, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1396, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1907, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691016, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@2697049"], "journal": "Infect Dis Model", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Killeen GF", "Kiware SS"]}
{"_id": "32691015|None", "id": "32691015", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Infect Dis Model; 2020 ; 5 409-441. doi:10.1016/j.idm.2020.06.008", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7334973", "type": "title", "authors": "Overton CE, Stage HB, Ahmad S, Curran-Sebastian J, Dark P, Das R, Fearon E, Felton T, Fyles M, Gent N, Hall I, House T, Lewkowicz H, Pang X, Pellis L, Sawko R, Ustianowski A, Vekaria B, Webb L, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Using statistics and mathematical modelling to understand infectious disease outbreaks: COVID-19 as an example.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003141", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infectious disease", "locations": [{"offset": 58, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 88, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 112, "text": "During an infectious disease outbreak, biases in the data and complexities of the underlying dynamics pose significant challenges in mathematically modelling the outbreak and designing policy. Motivated by the ongoing response to COVID-19, we provide a toolkit of statistical and mathematical models beyond the simple SIR-type differential equation models for analysing the early stages of an outbreak and assessing interventions. In particular, we focus on parameter estimation in the presence of known biases in the data, and the effect of non-pharmaceutical interventions in enclosed subpopulations, such as households and care homes. We illustrate these methods by applying them to the COVID-19 pandemic.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003141", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infectious disease", "locations": [{"offset": 122, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "8", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 342, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "9", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 802, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691015, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D003141", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "Infect Dis Model", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Overton CE", "Stage HB", "Ahmad S", "Curran-Sebastian J", "Dark P", "Das R", "Fearon E", "Felton T", "Fyles M", "Gent N", "Hall I", "House T", "Lewkowicz H", "Pang X", "Pellis L", "Sawko R", "Ustianowski A", "Vekaria B", "Webb L"]}
{"_id": "32691014|None", "id": "32691014", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Infect Dis Model; 2020 ; 5 405-408. doi:10.1016/j.idm.2020.06.004", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7334658", "type": "title", "authors": "Fisman DN, Greer AL, Tuite AR, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Bidirectional impact of imperfect mask use on reproduction number of COVID-19: A next generation matrix approach.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 69, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 114, "text": "The use of masks as a means of reducing transmission of COVID-19 outside healthcare settings has proved controversial. Masks are thought to have two modes of effect: they prevent infection with COVID-19 in wearers; and prevent transmission by individuals with subclinical infection. We used a simple next-generation matrix approach to estimate the conditions under which masks would reduce the reproduction number of COVID-19 under a threshold of 1. Our model takes into account the possibility of assortative mixing, where mask users interact preferentially with other mask users. We make 3 key observations: 1. Masks, even with suboptimal efficacy in both prevention of acquisition and transmission of infection, could substantially decrease the reproduction number for COVID-19 if widely used. 2. Widespread masking may be sufficient to suppress epidemics where R has been brought close to 1 via other measures (e.g., distancing). 3. \"Assortment\" within populations (the tendency for interactions between masked individuals to be more likely than interactions between masked and unmasked individuals) would rapidly erode the impact of masks. As such, mask uptake needs to be fairly universal to have an effect. This simple model suggests that widespread uptake of masking could be determinative in suppressing COVID-19 epidemics in regions with R(t) at or near 1.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 170, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 293, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 308, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 386, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 531, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 818, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 886, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1427, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691014, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D007239", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "Infect Dis Model", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Fisman DN", "Greer AL", "Tuite AR"]}
{"_id": "32691011|None", "id": "32691011", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Sci Adv; 2020 Jul ; 6 (28) 8097. doi:10.1126/sciadv.abb8097", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7319274", "type": "title", "authors": "Panda PK, Arul MN, Patel P, Verma SK, Luo W, Rubahn HG, Mishra YK, Suar M, Ahuja R, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Structure-based drug designing and immunoinformatics approach for SARS-CoV-2.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 66, "length": 10}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 78, "text": "The prevalence of respiratory illness caused by the novel SARS-CoV-2 virus associated with multiple organ failures is spreading rapidly because of its contagious human-to-human transmission and inadequate globalhealth care systems. Pharmaceutical repurposing, an effective drug development technique using existing drugs, could shorten development time and reduce costs compared to those of de novo drug discovery. We carried out virtual screening of antiviral compounds targeting the spike glycoprotein (S), main protease (Mpro), and the SARS-CoV-2 receptor binding domain (RBD)-angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2) complex of SARS-CoV-2. PC786, an antiviral polymerase inhibitor, showed enhanced binding affinity to all the targets. Furthermore, the postfusion conformation of the trimeric S protein RBD with ACE2 revealed conformational changes associated with PC786 drug binding. Exploiting immunoinformatics to identify T cell and B cell epitopes could guide future experimental studies with a higher probability of discovering appropriate vaccine candidates with fewer experiments and higher reliability.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012140", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "respiratory illness", "locations": [{"offset": 96, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 136, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 240, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "human", "locations": [{"offset": 249, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "43740568", "type": "Gene"}, "text": "S", "locations": [{"offset": 583, "length": 1}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "8673700", "type": "Gene"}, "text": "Mpro", "locations": [{"offset": 602, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 617, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "59272", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "41448"}, "text": "ACE2", "locations": [{"offset": 691, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 708, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "59272", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "41448"}, "text": "ACE2", "locations": [{"offset": 891, "length": 4}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691011, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "gene@43740568", "gene@59272", "gene@8673700", "species@2697049", "disease@MESH:D012140"], "journal": "Sci Adv", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Panda PK", "Arul MN", "Patel P", "Verma SK", "Luo W", "Rubahn HG", "Mishra YK", "Suar M", "Ahuja R"]}
{"_id": "32691007|None", "id": "32691007", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Open Forum Infect Dis; 2020 Jul ; 7 (7) 219. doi:10.1093/ofid/ofaa219", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7313774", "type": "title", "authors": "Chastain DB, Stitt TM, Ly PT, Henao-Mart\u00ednez AF, Franco-Paredes C, Osae SP, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Countermeasures to Coronavirus Disease 2019: Are Immunomodulators Rational Treatment Options-A Critical Review of the Evidence.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Coronavirus Disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 19, "length": 24}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 128, "text": "Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 is associated with higher concentrations of proinflammatory cytokines that lead to lung damage, respiratory failure, and resultant increased mortality. Immunomodulatory therapy has the potential to inhibit cytokines and quell the immune dysregulation. Controversial data found improved oxygenation after treatment with tocilizumab, an interleukin-6 inhibitor, sparking a wave of interest and resultant clinical trials evaluating immunomodulatory therapies. The purpose of this article is to assess potential proinflammatory targets and review the safety and efficacy of immunomodulatory therapies in managing patients with acute respiratory distress syndrome associated with coronavirus disease 2019.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2", "locations": [{"offset": 128, "length": 47}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D008171", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "lung damage", "locations": [{"offset": 259, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012131", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "respiratory failure", "locations": [{"offset": 272, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "mortality", "locations": [{"offset": 317, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C502936", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "tocilizumab", "locations": [{"offset": 495, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 785, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012128", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "acute respiratory distress syndrome", "locations": [{"offset": 799, "length": 35}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 851, "length": 24}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691007, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["chemical@MESH:C502936", "disease@MESH:D012128", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643", "disease@MESH:D012131", "species@9606", "disease@MESH:D008171", "species@2697049"], "journal": "Open Forum Infect Dis", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Chastain DB", "Stitt TM", "Ly PT", "Henao-Mart\u00ednez AF", "Franco-Paredes C", "Osae SP"]}
{"_id": "32691006|None", "id": "32691006", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J Tradit Complement Med; 2020 Jul ; 10 (4) 420-427. doi:10.1016/j.jtcme.2020.05.004", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7260602", "type": "title", "authors": "Panyod S, Ho CT, Sheen LY, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Dietary therapy and herbal medicine for COVID-19 prevention: A review and perspective.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "1407750", "type": "Species"}, "text": "herbal medicine", "locations": [{"offset": 20, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 40, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 87, "text": "A novel coronavirus disease (COVID-19), transmitted from humans to humans, has rapidly become the pandemic responsible for the current global health crisis. COVID-19 is caused by severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2), which is said to be of zoonotic origin. This review describes the etiology and signs and symptoms as well as the current allopathic therapy for COVID-19. Additionally, findings of previous studies on the immunomodulatory effects and antiviral activities of particular foods and herbs on influenza virus and coronaviruses have been collated, with the aim of promoting the use of dietary therapy and herbal medicine as COVID-19 preventive therapies, while specific drugs and vaccines are yet to be discovered or are still under development. The volume of existing reports is irrefutable evidence that foods and herbs possess a potential antiviral ability against SARS-CoV-2 and can prevent COVID-19. Foods and herbs could be used as dietary or complementary therapy to prevent infection and strengthen immunity, as antiviral agents for masks, as disinfectants to curb aerosol transmission, or as sanitizing agents to disinfect surfaces. However, these hypotheses need to be experimentally verified for SARS-CoV-2 and COVID-19 patients.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "novel coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 89, "length": 25}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 116, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "humans", "locations": [{"offset": 144, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "humans", "locations": [{"offset": 154, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 244, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2", "locations": [{"offset": 266, "length": 47}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 315, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D015047", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "zoonotic", "locations": [{"offset": 351, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 472, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "11308", "type": "Species"}, "text": "influenza virus", "locations": [{"offset": 615, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronaviruses", "locations": [{"offset": 635, "length": 13}]}, {"id": "34", "infons": {"identifier": "1407750", "type": "Species"}, "text": "herbal medicine", "locations": [{"offset": 726, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 745, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 989, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1016, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 1103, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 1328, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "40", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1343, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "41", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1352, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691006, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@11308", "disease@MESH:D015047", "species@2697049", "disease@MESH:D007239", "species@11118", "species@1407750"], "journal": "J Tradit Complement Med", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Panyod S", "Ho CT", "Sheen LY"]}
{"_id": "32691005|None", "id": "32691005", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J Tradit Complement Med; 2020 Jul ; 10 (4) 405-419. doi:10.1016/j.jtcme.2020.05.003", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7260130", "type": "title", "authors": "Fuzimoto AD, Isidoro C, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "The antiviral and coronavirus-host protein pathways inhibiting properties of herbs and natural compounds - Additional weapons in the fight against the COVID-19 pandemic?", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 18, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 151, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 170, "text": "Introduction: As of March 11th, 2020, the World Health Organization declared the COVID-19 outbreak a pandemic. Articles published after the SARS-CoV-1 (2002) epidemic suggest that the use of an herbal-drug integrative medical approach could have contributed to a lower fatality rate and a more rapid response in controlling the outbreak. Methods: Pubmed was searched for articles that investigated the antiviral properties and mechanisms of action of herbs or natural compounds against the SARS-coronavirus (CoV). Results: Forty-three (43) relevant papers were located. A general count rendered 450+ herbs and natural compounds with antiviral properties against the SARS-CoV and related viruses. From the 43 articles, thirty-one (31) uncovered the mechanisms of action of the natural substances able to oppose the coronavirus. Discussion: A series of herbs and natural compounds demonstrated moderate to strong antiviral activity. Research on many herbs-natural compounds also showed potent and significant inhibition of CoV-host protein pathways responsible for different phases of viral replication specifically targeting 3CLPRO, PLPRO, RdRp, helicase protein, S protein, N protein, 3a protein, Cathepsin L, Nsp1, Nsp3c, and ORF7a, and the S protein/ACE-2 interaction. Conclusion: The herbs-natural compounds with antiviral activity and that caused inhibition/blockade of the CoV-host protein pathways are potential therapeutic candidates. The homology between the SARS-CoV-1 and SARS-CoV-2 is around 80%. Thus, effective herbs-compounds for the former would likely be beneficial for the latter also depending on target protein similarities between the viruses. Here we provide the mechanistic bases supporting an integrative approach that includes natural compounds to fight coronavirus infections.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 251, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "694009", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV", "locations": [{"offset": 310, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "694009", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 660, "length": 16}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "CoV", "locations": [{"offset": 678, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "694009", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV", "locations": [{"offset": 836, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 984, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "CoV", "locations": [{"offset": 1191, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "CoV", "locations": [{"offset": 1548, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "694009", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV", "locations": [{"offset": 1637, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 1652, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D018352", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus infections", "locations": [{"offset": 1948, "length": 22}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691005, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D018352", "species@694009", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@2697049", "species@11118"], "journal": "J Tradit Complement Med", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Fuzimoto AD", "Isidoro C"]}
{"_id": "32691004|None", "id": "32691004", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "IDCases; 2020 ; 21 00895. doi:10.1016/j.idcr.2020.e00895", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7333611", "type": "title", "authors": "Ahmed AOE, Mohamed SF, Saleh AO, Al-Shokri SD, Ahmed K, Mohamed MFH, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Acute abdomen -like-presentation associated with SARS-CoV-2 infection.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2 infection", "locations": [{"offset": 49, "length": 20}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 71, "text": "As the cases of COVID-19 are flooding around the world, atypical presentations are being recognized, making the diagnosis challenging. Gastrointestinal symptoms and mild abdominal pain are common. However, severe abdominal pain associated with COVID-19 warranting surgical evaluation has been rarely described; recognizing such presentations and differentiating them from a surgical abdomen is critical to effectively and safely manage COVID-19 patients. Here we present a case of a middle-aged gentleman who developed features resembling secondary peritonitis. Eventually, he was found to have COVID-19 and was managed conservatively. In this report, we discuss his management course, and we explore pertinent relevant literature.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 87, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D012817", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Gastrointestinal symptoms", "locations": [{"offset": 206, "length": 25}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D015746", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "abdominal pain", "locations": [{"offset": 241, "length": 14}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D015746", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "abdominal pain", "locations": [{"offset": 284, "length": 14}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 315, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 507, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 516, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D010534", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "peritonitis", "locations": [{"offset": 620, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 666, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691004, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D015746", "species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D012817", "disease@MESH:D010534"], "journal": "IDCases", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Ahmed AOE", "Mohamed SF", "Saleh AO", "Al-Shokri SD", "Ahmed K", "Mohamed MFH"]}
{"_id": "32691003|None", "id": "32691003", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "IDCases; 2020 ; 21 00869. doi:10.1016/j.idcr.2020.e00869", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7301793", "type": "title", "authors": "Ajuria-Illarramendi O, Martinez-Lorca A, Ordu\u00f1a-Diez MDP, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "[18F]FDG-PET/CT in different COVID-19 phases.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 29, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 46, "text": "PET/CT is an hybrid technique which allows both morfological and metabolical evalutaion. Three different morphometeabolical patterns are presented which reflect the evolutive phases of the COVID-19. This findings may help the clinician determine the correct treatment and security measure that need to be taken aaccording to the phase of the disease.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 235, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32691003, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "IDCases", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Ajuria-Illarramendi O", "Martinez-Lorca A", "Ordu\u00f1a-Diez MDP"]}
{"_id": "32691002|None", "id": "32691002", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Integr Med Res; 2020 Sep ; 9 (3) 100470. doi:10.1016/j.imr.2020.100470", "year": "2020", "article-id_pmc": "PMC7335489", "type": "title", "authors": "Lee BJ, Lee JA, Kim KI, Choi JY, Jung HJ, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "A consensus guideline of herbal medicine for coronavirus disease 2019.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "1407750", "type": "Species"}, "text": "herbal medicine", "locations": [{"offset": 25, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "coronavirus disease 2019", "locations": [{"offset": 45, "length": 24}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 71, "text": "Background: The Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2), which originated in Wuhan, Hubei Province, China in late December 2019, is the cause of ongoing pandemic. We analyzed the symptoms of SARS-CoV-2, a classification of the Chinese medicine dialectic and treatment regimen, and promptly enacted the recommendation of Korean medicine preparations in herbal medicine covered under domestic medical insurance benefits depending on the circumstances in our country. Method: The clinical practice guideline (CPG) for the treatment of SARS-CoV-2 was developed based on consensus from a group of experts. Results: Two kinds of herbal medicines (HM) were recommended for the prevention of SARS-CoV-2; Youngyopaedoc-san plus Bojungikgitang, and Youngyopaedoc-san plus Saengmaek-san. Two herbal preparations were recommended for people with a history of exposure to SARS-CoV-2; Youngyopaedoc-san plus Bulhwangeumjeonggi-san, and Youngyopaedoc-san plus Bojungikgi-tang. Three herbal preparations were recommended for mildly symptomatic COVID-19 patients; Youngyopaedoc-san plus Galgunhaegui-tang was recommended for those without pneumonia with wind-warmth disease invading the lungs; Sosiho-tang plus Bulhwangeumjeonggi-san was recommended for those with dampness-heat disease in the lungs. For the recovery stage, Samchulkunbi-tang plus Saengmaek-san, or Samchulkunbi-tang plus Chungseuiki-tang was recommended. Conclusion: The CPG was developed to guide the use of Korean herbal medicine in the treatment of SARS-CoV-2, and it is expected that this will be the basis for providing proper treatment of similar infectious diseases in the future.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "694009", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 87, "length": 45}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 134, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 281, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "1407750", "type": "Species"}, "text": "herbal medicine", "locations": [{"offset": 442, "length": 15}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 622, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 774, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 912, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 949, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1118, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 1127, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D011014", "type":