{"_id": "32690752|None", "id": "32690752", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "BMJ Open; 2020 Jul 20 ; 10 (7) 039334. doi:10.1136/bmjopen-2020-039334", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Williams SN, Armitage CJ, Tampe T, Dienes K, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Public perceptions and experiences of social distancing and social isolation during the COVID-19 pandemic: a UK-based focus group study.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 88, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 137, "text": "OBJECTIVE: This study explored UK public perceptions and experiences of social distancing and social isolation related to the COVID-19 pandemic. DESIGN: This qualitative study comprised five focus groups, carried out online during the early stages of the UK's stay at home order ('lockdown'), and analysed using a thematic approach. SETTING: Focus groups took place via online videoconferencing. PARTICIPANTS: Participants (n=27) were all UK residents aged 18 years and older, representing a range of gender, ethnic, age and occupational backgrounds. RESULTS: Qualitative analysis revealed four main themes: (1) loss-participants' loss of (in-person) social interaction, loss of income and loss of structure and routine led to psychological and emotional 'losses' such as loss of motivation, loss of meaning and loss of self-worth; (2) criticisms of government communication-participants reported a lack of trust in government and a lack of clarity in the guidelines around social distancing and isolation; (3) adherence-participants reported high self-adherence to social distancing guidelines but reported seeing or hearing of non-adherence in others; (4) uncertainty around social reintegration and the future-some participants felt they would have lingering concerns over social contact while others were eager to return to high levels of social activity.Most participants, and particularly those in low-paid or precarious employment, reported feeling that the social distancing and isolation associated with COVID-19 policy has had negative impacts on their mental health and well-being during the early stages of the UK's 'lockdown'. CONCLUSIONS: A rapid response is necessary in terms of public health programming to mitigate the mental health impacts of COVID-19 social distancing and isolation. Social distancing and isolation 'exit strategies' must account for the fact that, although some individuals will voluntarily or habitually continue to socially distance, others will seek high levels of social engagement as soon as possible.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 263, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "PARTICIPANTS", "locations": [{"offset": 533, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Participants", "locations": [{"offset": 547, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "15", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "participants", "locations": [{"offset": 754, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "16", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "participants", "locations": [{"offset": 1012, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "17", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "participants", "locations": [{"offset": 1158, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "18", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "participants", "locations": [{"offset": 1355, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "participants", "locations": [{"offset": 1501, "length": 12}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1650, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 1899, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32690752, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "BMJ Open", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Williams SN", "Armitage CJ", "Tampe T", "Dienes K"]}
{"_id": "32690631|None", "id": "32690631", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "BMJ Open Diabetes Res Care; 2020 Jul ; 8 (1) . doi:10.1136/bmjdrc-2020-001520", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Gujral UP, Johnson L, Nielsen J, Vellanki P, Haw JS, Davis GM, Weber MB, Pasquel FJ, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Preparedness cycle to address transitions in diabetes care during the COVID-19 pandemic and future outbreaks.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 45, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 70, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 110, "text": "The COVID-19 pandemic is considered a mass casualty incident of the most severe nature leading to unearthed uncertainties around management, prevention, and care. As of July 2020, more than twelve million people have tested positive for COVID-19 globally and more than 500 000 people have died. Patients with diabetes are among the most severely affected during this pandemic. Healthcare systems have made emergent changes to adapt to this public health crisis, including changes in diabetes care. Adaptations in diabetes care in the hospital (ie, changes in treatment protocols according to clinical status, diabetes technology implementation) and outpatient setting (telemedicine, mail delivery, patient education, risk stratification, monitoring) have been improvised to address this challenge. We describe how to respond to the current public health crisis focused on diabetes care in the USA. We present strategies to address and evaluate transitions in diabetes care occurring in the immediate short-term (ie, response and mitigation), as well as phases to adapt and enhance diabetes care during the months and years to come while also preparing for future pandemics (ie, recovery, surveillance, and preparedness). Implementing multidimensional frameworks may help identify gaps in care, alleviate initial demands, mitigate potential harms, and improve implementation strategies and outcomes in the future.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "19", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 114, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "20", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 315, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "21", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 347, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "22", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 387, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "23", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "died", "locations": [{"offset": 399, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "Patients", "locations": [{"offset": 405, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 419, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 593, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 623, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 719, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "outpatient", "locations": [{"offset": 759, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patient", "locations": [{"offset": 808, "length": 7}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 982, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 1069, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003920", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "diabetes", "locations": [{"offset": 1191, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32690631, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "disease@MESH:D003920", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643"], "journal": "BMJ Open Diabetes Res Care", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Gujral UP", "Johnson L", "Nielsen J", "Vellanki P", "Haw JS", "Davis GM", "Weber MB", "Pasquel FJ"]}
{"_id": "32690628|None", "id": "32690628", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Sci Transl Med; 2020 Jul 20 . doi:10.1126/scitranslmed.abc9396", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Erasmus JH, Khandhar AP, O'Connor MA, Walls AC, Hemann EA, Murapa P, Archer J, Leventhal S, Fuller JT, Lewis TB, Draves KE, Randall S, Guerriero KA, Duthie MS, Carter D, Reed SG, Hawman DW, Feldmann H, Gale M, Veesler D, Berglund P, Heydenburg Fuller D, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "An alphavirus-derived replicon RNA vaccine induces SARS-CoV-2 neutralizing antibody and T cell responses in mice and nonhuman primates.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 51, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "10090", "type": "Species"}, "text": "mice", "locations": [{"offset": 108, "length": 4}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 136, "text": "The COVID-19 pandemic, caused by infection with the SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus, is having a deleterious impact on health services and the global economy, highlighting the urgent need for an effective vaccine. Such a vaccine would need to rapidly confer protection after one or two doses and would need to be manufactured using components suitable for scale-up. Here, we developed an alphavirus-derived replicon RNA vaccine candidate, repRNA-CoV2S, encoding the SARS-CoV-2 spike (S) protein. The RNA replicons were formulated with Lipid InOrganic Nanoparticles (LION) that were designed to enhance vaccine stability, delivery, and immunogenicity. We show that a single intramuscular injection of the LION/repRNA-CoV2S vaccine in mice elicited robust production of anti-SARS-CoV-2 S protein IgG antibody isotypes indicative of a Type 1 T helper cell response. A prime/boost regimen induced potent T cell responses in mice including antigen-specific responses in lung and spleen. Prime-only immunization of aged (17-month old) mice induced smaller immune responses compared to young mice, but this difference was abrogated by booster immunization. Importantly, in nonhuman primates, prime-only immunization in one intramuscular injection site or prime/boost immunizations in 5 intramuscular injection sites elicited modest T cell responses and robust antibody responses. The antibody responses persisted for at least 70 days and neutralized SARS-CoV-2 at titers comparable to those in human serum samples collected from individuals convalescing from COVID-19. These data support further development of LION/repRNA-CoV2S as a vaccine candidate for prophylactic protection against SARS-CoV-2 infection.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 140, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "25", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 169, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "26", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 188, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "27", "infons": {"identifier": "11118", "type": "Species"}, "text": "coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 199, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "28", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "CoV2", "locations": [{"offset": 573, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "29", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "SARS-CoV-2", "locations": [{"offset": 593, "length": 10}]}, {"id": "30", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D008055", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "Lipid", "locations": [{"offset": 662, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "31", "infons": {"identifier": "9689", "type": "Species"}, "text": "LION", "locations": [{"offset": 693, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "9689", "type": "Species"}, "text": "LION", "locations": [{"offset": 831, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "33"