{"_id": "32690572|None", "id": "32690572", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "BMJ Case Rep; 2020 Jul 20 ; 13 (7) . doi:10.1136/bcr-2020-237427", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Dahl Mathiasen V, Jensen-Fangel S, Skov K, Leth S, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Uneventful case of COVID-19 in a kidney transplant recipient.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 19, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 62, "text": "Kidney transplant recipients have been reported at a particularly high risk of severe COVID-19 illness due to chronic immunosuppression and coexisting conditions. Yet, here we describe a remarkably mild case of COVID-19 in a 62-year-old female who had a kidney transplantation 10 years earlier due to autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease. The patient was admitted for 1 day; immunosuppressive therapy with tacrolimus and low-dose prednisolone was continued; and the patient recovered successfully without the use of antiviral agents or oxygen therapy. The case demonstrates that kidney transplant recipients are not necessarily severely affected by COVID-19. Withdrawal of immunosuppressive therapy could be associated with poorer outcomes and should not be implemented thoughtlessly.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 148, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 273, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007690", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease", "locations": [{"offset": 363, "length": 44}]}, {"id": "14", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "tex