{"_id": "32690366|None", "id": "32690366", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Transfus. Apher. Sci.; 2020 Jul 15 102878. doi:10.1016/j.transci.2020.102878", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Gupta AM, Ojha S, Poojary M, S H S, Nagaraju P, Dhokle R, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Organization of the outdoor blood donation drives amid novel coronavirus pandemic and national lockdown: An experience from a tertiary care oncology institution in India.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "2697049", "type": "Species"}, "text": "novel coronavirus", "locations": [{"offset": 55, "length": 17}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 171, "text": "The conduct of blood donation drives became difficult amid novel coronavirus disease pandemic and national lockdown. Despite no restriction for the outdoor blood donation drives, voluntary blood donor organizations (VBDOs) and individual donors became apprehensive regarding the possible risk of spread of the infection during blood donation. Various confidence-building measures were taken to decrease this hesitation. Numerous preventive measures were taken at the blood bank and at the donation venue to limit the possible risk of the spread of infection. With the help of these measures, the confidence of the individual blood donors and the VBDOs was restored and multiple blood drives were organized.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "novel coronavirus disease", "locations": [{"offset": 230, "length": 25}]}, {"id": "6", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 481, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 719, "length": 9}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32690366, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D007239", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "species@2697049"], "journal": "Transfus. Apher. Sci.", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Gupta AM", "Ojha S", "Poojary M", "S H S", "Nagaraju P", "Dhokle R"]}
{"_id": "32690356|None", "id": "32690356", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Paediatr Respir Rev; 2020 Jun 20 . doi:10.1016/j.prrv.2020.06.015", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Pons-\u00d2dena M, Valls A, Grifols J, Farr\u00e9 R, Cambra Lasosa FJ, Rubin BK, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "COVID-19 and respiratory support devices.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 42, "text": "There are significant logistical challenges to providing respiratory support devices, beyond simple oxygen flow, when centres run out of supplies or do not have these devices at all, such as in low resource settings. At the peak of the COVID-19 crisis, it was extremely difficult to import medical equipment and supplies, because most countries prohibited the medical industry from selling outside of their own countries. As a consequence, engineering teams worldwide volunteered to develop emergency devices, and medical experts in mechanical ventilation helped to guide the design and evaluation of prototypes. Although regulations vary among countries, given the emergency situation, some Regulatory Agencies facilitated expedited procedures. However, laboratory and animal model testing are crucial to minimize the potential risk for patients when treated with a device that may worsen clinical outcome if poorly designed or misused.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D010100", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "oxygen", "locations": [{"offset": 142, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "6", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 278, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 880, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32690356, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["species@9606", "chemical@MESH:D010100", "disease@MESH:C000657245"], "journal": "Paediatr Respir Rev", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Pons-\u00d2dena M", "Valls A", "Grifols J", "Farr\u00e9 R", "Cambra Lasosa FJ", "Rubin BK"]}
{"_id": "32690355|None", "id": "32690355", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Paediatr Respir Rev; 2020 Jun 11 . doi:10.1016/j.prrv.2020.06.005", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Fitzgerald DA, Nunn K, Isaacs D, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Consequences of physical distancing emanating from the COVID-19 pandemic: An Australian perspective.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 55, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 101, "text": "The sobering reality of the COVID-19 pandemic is that it has brought people together at home at a time when we want them apart in the community. This will bring both benefits and challenges. It will affect people differently based upon their age, health status, resilience, family support structures, and socio-economic background. This article will assess the impact in high income countries like Australia, where the initial wave of infection placed the elderly at the greatest risk of death whilst the protective measures of physical distancing, self-isolation, increased awareness of hygiene practices, and school closures with distance learning has had considerable impact on children and families acutely and may have ramifications for years to come.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "8", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 129, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "9", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 170, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "10", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "people", "locations": [{"offset": 307, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "11", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D007239", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "infection", "locations": [{"offset": 536, "length": 9}]}, {"id": "12", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "death", "locations": [{"offset": 589, "length": 5}]}, {"id": "13", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "children", "locations": [{"offset": 782, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32690355, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:D007239", "species@9606", "disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643"], "journal": "Paediatr Respir Rev", "year": 2020, "authors": ["Fitzgerald DA", "Nunn K", "Isaacs D"]}
{"_id": "32690354|None", "id": "32690354", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Paediatr Respir Rev; 2020 Jun 18 . doi:10.1016/j.prrv.2020.06.013", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "McBryde ES, Meehan MT, Adegboye OA, Adekunle AI, Caldwell JM, Pak A, Rojas DP, Williams BM, Trauer JM, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Role of modelling in COVID-19 policy development.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 21, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 50, "text": "Models have played an important role in policy development to address the COVID-19 outbreak from its emergence in China to the current global pandemic. Early projections of international spread influenced travel restrictions and border closures. Model projections based on the virus's infectiousness demonstrated its pandemic potential, which guided the global response to and prepared countries for increases in hospitalisations and deaths. Tracking the impact of distancing and movement policies and behaviour changes has been critical in evaluating these decisions. Models have provided insights into the epidemiological differences between higher and lower income countries, as well as vulnerable population groups within countries to help design fit-for-purpose policies. Economic evaluation and policies have combined epidemic models and traditional economic models to address the economic consequences of COVID-19, which have informed policy calls for easing restrictions. Social contact and mobility models have allowed evaluation of the pathways to safely relax mobility restrictions and distancing measures. Finally, models can consider future end-game scenarios, including how suppression can be achieved and the impact of different vaccination strategies.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 124, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "6", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "deaths", "locations": [{"offset": 484, "length": 6}]}, {"id": "7", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19", "locations": [{"offset": 962, "length": 8}]}], "relations": []}], "relations": [], "pmid": 32690354, "pmcid": null, "created": {"$date": 1595454010467}, "accessions": ["disease@MESH:C000657245", "disease@MESH:D003643"], "journal": "Paediatr Respir Rev", "year": 2020, "authors": ["McBryde ES", "Meehan MT", "Adegboye OA", "Adekunle AI", "Caldwell JM", "Pak A", "Rojas DP", "Williams BM", "Trauer JM"]}
{"_id": "32690352|None", "id": "32690352", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "J. Autoimmun.; 2020 Jul 16 102523. doi:10.1016/j.jaut.2020.102523", "year": "2020", "type": "title", "authors": "Moreno-P\u00e9rez O, Andres M, Leon-Ramirez JM, S\u00e1nchez-Pay\u00e1 J, Rodr\u00edguez JC, S\u00e1nchez R, Garc\u00eda-Sevila R, Boix V, Gil J, Merino E, ", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Experience with tocilizumab in severe COVID-19 pneumonia after 80 days of follow-up: A retrospective cohort study.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "2", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C502936", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "tocilizumab", "locations": [{"offset": 16, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19 pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 38, "length": 18}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 115, "text": "OBJECTIVES: To describe the clinical characteristics and predictors of major outcomes in patients treated with tocilizumab (TCZ) for severe COVID-19 pneumonia. PATIENTS AND METHODS: Case series of all sequential patients with severe COVID-19 pneumonia treated with TCZ at an Academic Spanish hospital (March 12 - May 2, 2020). Clinical outcomes: death, length of hospital stay. An early clinical response to TCZ (48-72 h after the administration) was assessed by variations in respiratory function markers, Brescia COVID Respiratory Severity Scale (BCRSS), inflammatory parameters, and patients' and physicians' opinion. Associations were tested by multiple logistic regression. RESULTS: From a cohort of 236 patients, 77 patients treated with TCZ were included (median age 62 years (IQR 53.0-72.0), 64.9% were males), 42.9% had Charlson index >=3; hypertension (41.6%), obesity (34.7%), and diabetes (20.8%). Median follow-up was 83.0 days (78.0-86.5), no patient was readmitted. ICU admission was required for 42 (54.5%), invasive mechanical ventilation in 38 (49.4%) and 10 patients died (12.9% global, 23.8% at ICU admitted). After multivariate adjustment, TCZ response by BCRSS (OR 0.03 (0.01-0.68), p = 0.028), and Charlson index (OR 3.54 (1.20-10.44), p = 0.022) has been identified as independent factors associated with mortality. Median of hospital stay was 16.0 days (11.0-23.0); BCRSS, physician subjective and D-dimer response were associated with shorter hospitalization stay. CONCLUSIONS: In a Mediterranean cohort, use of tocilizumab for severe COVID-19 show 12.9% of mortality. Early TCZ-response by BCRSS and low comorbidity were associated with increased survival. Early TCZ-response was related to shorter median hospital stay.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 204, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C502936", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "tocilizumab", "locations": [{"offset": 226, "length": 11}]}, {"id": "34", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C502936", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "TCZ", "locations": [{"offset": 239, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19 pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 255, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "PATIENTS", "locations": [{"offset": 275, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "patients", "locations": [{"offset": 327, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C000657245", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "COVID-19 pneumonia", "locations": [{"offset": 348, "length": 18}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:C502936", "type": "Chemical"}, "text": "TCZ", "locations": [{"offset": 380, "length": 3}]}, {"id": "40", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003643", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "death", "locations": [{"offset": 461, "length": 5}]}, {"id":